# 🛡️ PART 2 — Cache bypass rules (critical systems like payments/auth)

This is where big companies become strict.

---

## ⚠️ Problem

Cache is great for speed, but:

> Some systems MUST never rely on cached results

Examples:

* payments 💳
* authentication 🔐
* security logic 🛡️
* billing systems 💰

---

## 🧠 Solution: “Always-fresh enforcement”

You define **no-cache rules per project**

---

## 🧩 1. Tag critical apps

```json id="tags1"
{
  "name": "payments-api",
  "tags": ["critical:yes"]
}
```

```json id="tags2"
{
  "name": "auth-api",
  "tags": ["critical:yes"]
}
```

---

## 🚫 2. Disable cache for critical targets

In `project.json`:

```json id="nocache1"
{
  "targets": {
    "build": {
      "executor": "nx:run-commands",
      "options": {
        "command": "npm run build"
      },
      "cache": false
    }
  }
}
```

---

## 🧠 3. Force CI re-execution for critical apps

```bash id="force1"
npx nx affected \
  --target=test \
  --exclude=critical:yes \
  --base=origin/main
```

AND separately:

```bash id="force2"
npx nx run payments-api:test --skip-nx-cache=false
npx nx run auth-api:test --skip-nx-cache=false
```

👉 Translation:

* normal apps → cached allowed
* critical apps → always re-run

---

## 🔥 4. “Double validation pattern” (FAANG trick)

Critical services run twice:

### Layer 1 (Nx cache allowed)

* fast feedback

### Layer 2 (fresh execution)

* no cache allowed

```bash id="double1"
nx run auth-api:test --skip-nx-cache
nx run payments-api:test --skip-nx-cache
```

---

# 🧠 Why this is safe

Big companies assume:

| Layer          | Purpose              |
| -------------- | -------------------- |
| Nx cache       | speed                |
| CI re-run      | correctness          |
| E2E tests      | system safety        |
| no-cache zones | critical correctness |

